Hi CD,
Starting in the 2024 offseason, our team has been making a deliberate effort to improve our wiring. One of the improvements we have made is by ferruling can wire. For the most part this has worked great- the number of can failures we have had has dramatically dropped.
However, whenever there was a can failure, it originated from the sparkflex can wire on our algae mechanism. These ferrules seem to have a much harder time with sparkflex can than other can. Our sparkflex can constantly falls out of the ferrules they were crimped to, even with none to minimal stress on the wire.
When we replaced the sparkflex, the same phenomena still occurred.
My leading theory is that the sparkflex can wire is a slightly smaller gauge of wire than the normal can used throughout the robot.
Is my theory correct, or am I completely off here?

Your hunch is correct. The standard CAN wire for FRC is 22 AWG, while the SparkFLEX uses 26 AWG wire. It’s ridiculous and super

REV Robotics - SPARK Flex and NEO Vortex General Forum
Due to mechanical constraints related to the comolded strain relief part and the internal clearances, we needed to go with 26 AWG wire. 26 AWG wire does in fact have less tensile strength than 24 or 22 AWG wire. However, we don’t believe it affects the usability or durability in a significant way, especially if following good wiring and strain relief practices.
